I always dislike closing comments because they frequently put a spin of finality on things. Here, in this or any other forum on the Vietnam War, I feel there will never be any final comment, final conclusion, or final point of view on its roots, the conduct of combat, or the aftermath.<br><br>
What has impressed me the most in this discussion is the willingness of people to express their thoughts and a willingness of people to listen. This one thing I<br>
found to be most valuable. It matters not that there be agreement on everything. What matters is the demonstration of the capacity to converge, to toss imaginary flowers and stones once in a while, to risk the exposure of some of our more sensitive points of view, and to come away whole again a little more enriched by the experience. That is what<br>
this seems to be really all about.<br><br>
There will be a new comet visible soon. Although this discussion was not cosmic in any sense, we all flew a little closer to the sun and became visible.<br><br>
Like the comet, we will fade again until our next trip by the sun.<br><br>
Comets, however, are never, ever, forgotten. In some small way, neither will our discussion, even if it persists only in our minds. <br><br>
The record of our deliberations being available publicly and open for comments is extraordinarily important. I recall Prof. Grivetti reaching out several months ago, testing the waters for ideas, information, and whatever else was out there. I think he did that for some very good reasons. History tends to become as two dimensional as<br>
the pages in the book upon which it is written. Unlike oral traditions which always pass along emotions and views in an interactive sense from the storyteller to the listeners, no matter how many generations of the story pass by, we characteristically relegate the care of history to<br>
dusty moth-eaten repositories ruled by &quot;experts&quot; who are usually too stuck on themselves to explain anything you do not already understand.<br><br>
I hope our work here brings some life for a while to this topic. The Vietnam War history, like so many other histories, will inevitably become featureless and stale theoretical renditions in time, destined to bore thousands of students to death in those dreaded seventh period<br>
Friday afternoon classes just before spring break.&quot;<br><br>
This is not farewell to all, but a just a farewell to this remarkable site. I'll be on line at &quot;the new place&quot; as soon as *it* is on line! There is much left for me to accomplish with myself and to share with the world.<br><br>
